char.label: Lateral-line neuromasts (Some fossils are assumed here to have possessed neuromasts when they possess sensory-line canals, since no extant vertebrate is known to have canals but no neuromast.

Pituitary control of melanophores (This character may be correlated with the presence/absence of a pineal foramen in fossils. Absence of a pineal foramen and thus of a photosensory pineal organ would preclude pituitary control of melanophores.)
Two types of giant Mauthner cells in the central nervous system
Skull (This refers to any cranial component, i.e. splanchno- or neurocrania!.)
Dorsally closed cartilaginous or calcified braincase (neurocranium)
Transversely biting teeth (This generally refers to horny teeth of lampreys and hagfishes, but can potentially be extended to the mineralized teeth of conodonts.)
Trunk and tail musculature with chevron-shaped muscle blocks (In mineralized fossils, the arrangement of the musculature may be inferred from that of the scales, as in anaspids, arandaspids, etc.)
Radials in fins absent (In many mineralized fossils, the presence of radials is inferred from the alignment of the overlying scales or fin rays.)
Numerous and closely set radials in unpaired fins (In many fossils, this character is inferred from the arrangement of the scale rows corresponding to the position of the underlying radials.)
Separate dorsal fin (This refers to a separate fin anterior to epichordal lobe in the case of forms having a hypocercal tail.)

Tail (Although apparently pad-shaped, isocercal or diphycercal, the tail of heterostracans is coded here as hypocercal, because it is assumed to be derived from the hypocercal tail of generalized thelodont type by enlargement of the epichordal radials, as suggested by the 'fork-tailed' thelodonts which display the same tail morphology as heterostracans. The actual path of the notochord has, however, never been observed in heterostracans.)

Paired fin folds or fins (This refers to any lateral skin fold, be it with radials and radial musculature or not. The small lateral skin fold of the extant hagfish Neomyxine is not considered here as a fin fold.)
Paired fin folds or fins concentrated in the pectoral or epibranchial regions
Gill openings arranged in a posteriorly slanting line
Olfactory organ unpaired or with closely set and confluent nasal sacs
Olfactory organ paired with entirely separated nasal sacs
Nasohypophysial duct posteriorly closed and serving only as a common 'nostril'

Two vertical semicircular canals forming distinct loops (This refers to the distinct canals of e.g. osteostracans, galeaspids or gnathostomes, in contrast to those of lampreys, which lie against the vestibular division of the labyrinth.)
Vagus and glossopharyngeus nerves included in occipital region
Head endoskeleton expanded into a massive shield covering the gills,
Oakleaf-shaped tubercles or odontodes in ornamentation
Large median dorsal and ventral dermal shields in head
Opercular flaps on external branchial openings
Preanal skin fold or scale ridge
Scales made up by a single odontode (microsquamose)
Scales made up by several odontodes (macrosquamose) and diamond-shaped
Scales made up by several odontodes (macrosquamose) and rod-shaped
Sucking disc with an annular cartilage around mouth,
